K> .I'd hope that cellular phone designers would not make mobile terminals
 > .that constantly communicate with the cell base part of the system when
 > .a car's electrical circuits are turned on, but only when the system
 > .is "off the hook" (preparing to make a phone call).

CellPhones can also RECEIVE calls.  The do this (obviously) when they're
on-hook.  In order to determine which cell to use, the system has to be
able to locate a specific unit geographically, even when it's on-hook.

K> .The extreme case of eavesdropping reportedly happened in the UK, in
 > .which when a 150 khz tone was applied to the phone line's wires from
 > .the central office, conversations in the house could be heard, even
 > .though the phone was hung up. Nasty indeed!

This requires some "special facility" added to the phone.  A "plain
vanilla" phone doesn't respond to the trigger tone.

